{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":7528,"record_hash":"sha256:6b8b131a25c7af852ced4f21bfc061a2d710a2c63746b83043db52d16cd9d49e","timestamp":"2026-05-20T16:57:41.366Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 45b95f\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 5628\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of a\ncapture turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A capture turn layer would preserve that missing context without\nforcing us to immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit,\nchange, or pull request.\n\n## V1 Contract\n\nImplement v1 around persisted capture observations, derived indexes, and\nread-time association. Do not persist inferred ownership.\n\nPersisted hierarchy:\n\n```text\nproject\n  session\n    capture turns\n      transcript records\n```\n\nStorage shape:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n```\n\nCore rules:\n\n- A capture turn is created only when capture accepts at least one new\n  transcript record.\n- `TurnDetail.records` is an ordered array and is authoritative for rendering\n  order within the capture turn.\n- Backfilled capture turns may contain many logical conversation/provider turns,\n  so records must carry provider/display grouping metadata when available.\n- `turn_key` is `sha256-<32 lowercase hex chars>`, computed from UTF-8 stored\n  `session_key`, `s\n[TRUNCATED]\nnch id when the workspace snapshot exposes a\n  durable id, otherwise normalized full refname when available, with display\n  name kept separately for UI\n- review key material: strongest available review identity, for example\n  `github-pr:owner/repo#1284`, `pull-request:<remote-url-hash>#1284`, or\n  `gitbutler-review:<review-id>`\n- change key material: canonical bytes/text for the GitButler change id\n\nHash branch, review, and change key material before embedding it in GitMeta key\nnames. Keep the readable canonical value in `observed_targets` and the\nenvironment snapshot.\n\nFor worktree file paths, store relative paths plainly on the capture turn\nsnapshot. They are useful handoff context and keep explanations understandable.\nGuard against pathological cases such as generated trees, vendor drops, or giant\nlockfile-driven changes by storing a count and truncated flag alongside a capped\nsorted path list.\n\nUse a path cap of 256 entries per path list. Keep the total count even when the\nlist is not truncated. It is redundant in the common case, but useful for\nconsistent reads and essential when `*_truncated = true`.\n\nExample worktree shape:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"files\": [\"src/foo.rs\", \"src/bar.rs\"],\n  \"file_count\": 2,\n  \"files_truncated\": false\n}\n```\n\nDo not store per-commit file lists in the primitive layer. They were useful for\nearly scoring sketches, but they add capture-time cost and storage volume before\nwe have a product consumer. A review or handoff feature can derive richer\ncommit/path evidence later if the UX needs it.\n\nDo not store commit message summaries in the capture turn snapshot. Commit\nsubjects can be read from Git by `commit_id` when a UI needs them, and they are\nnot useful association evidence.\n\nSnapshot status values:\n\n- `complete`: worktree and stack/branch observations were collected\n- `partial`: some observations were collected but one or more optional pieces\n  failed\n- `failed`: no useful environment observation was collected\n\nFor failed or partial snapshots, store a coarse `error_kind` if useful for\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T16:57:41.366Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}